data.content:
These are two distinct C# 15 breaking changes:

---

### Issue 1: `&&` with `dynamic` and interface operators

The `&&` operator desugars to:
```
operator false(left) ? left : operator &(left, right)
```
This requires **both** `operator true`/`false` **and** `operator &` on the same type.

**C# 15 change:** The compiler now statically validates the `&&` pattern on the left operand's type, even when the right operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the entire expression was deferred to runtime.

`IFilter` defines `operator true`/`false` but **no `operator &`**, so the `&&` pattern is incomplete.

**Fixes:**
```csharp
// Option A: Add operator & to the interface
interface IFilter
{
    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;
    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;
    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;
}

// Option B: Avoid && with dynamic — use explicit logic
void Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    IFilter combined = left;
    if (left) // uses operator true
        combined = (IFilter)(left & right); // runtime-bound &
}

// Option C: Cast away from dynamic first
void Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    var combined = left && (IFilter)right;
}
```

---

### Issue 2: `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518

CS0518 ("Predefined type not defined or imported") means the compiler needs a BCL type that isn't in your referenced assemblies.

C# 15 newly supports `ref readonly` return types on lambdas with natural delegate type inference. The compiler synthesizes a delegate type and needs a specific `System.Runtime.CompilerServices` attribute to encode the `ref readonly` return — this type was **added in .NET 11**.

**Likely cause:** SDK/TFM mismatch — your project file doesn't fully target .NET 11, or you have stale package references.

**Fixes:**
```xml
<!-- Ensure your .csproj properly targets .NET 11 -->
<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>
<LangVersion>15</LangVersion>
```

Or use an explicit delegate type as a workaround:
```csharp
delegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();

public static void M()
{
    RefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;  // no synthesized delegate needed
}
```
